cards.back: $P(A\mid B)=\dfrac{P(B\mid A)\,P(A)}{P(B)}$. Posterior = likelihood  prior divided by evidence.
A prior probability is the initial probability of an event obtained before new information is observed; used as P(A) in Bayes' theorem.
A posterior probability is the revised probability after incorporating new information; computed as P(A|B) via Bayes' theorem.
Assume event A has occurred and compute the probability that event B occurs under that assumption; that's P(B|A).

cards.front: What does the likelihood P(B|A) represent?
cards.back: P(B|A) is the probability of observing the new evidence B given that hypothesis/event A is true; it weights how compatible A is with B.

cards.front: Define evidence P(B) in Bayes' context
cards.back: Evidence P(B) is the marginal probability of observing B: $P(B)=\sum_i P(B\mid A_i)P(A_i)$ when {A_i} partition the sample space.
$P(A_j\mid B)=\dfrac{P(B\mid A_j)P(A_j)}{\sum_i P(B\mid A_i)P(A_i)}$, for a partition {A_i}.
The events {A_i} must form a partition of the sample space (mutually exclusive and exhaustive) so the denominator sums all alternatives.
Bayes models updating: an initial (prior) belief is revised after observing a subsequent event (evidence), producing a posterior belief.

cards.front: Bayes' role in industrial quality control
cards.back: Use Bayes to revise the probability a defective part came from a given source or machine after test outcomes, combining priors and test likelihoods.
